From his time as a PM, Glasgow realized that user research, which was becom=
ing more important as competition increased, still operated on a timeframe =
that was out of sync with the rest of the business. Software hasn=E2=80=99t=
 worked on quarterly or annual release cycles for a long time -- companies =
ship changes and improvements to their product and website every minute -- =
but user research still typically works on a much slower cycle.=C2=A0
If you=E2=80=99ve worked in a customer facing or user research role, the st=
andard research process might be familiar: quarterly projects, lots of plan=
ning and survey design, email surveys with 2-5% response rates, then tons a=
nd tons of unstructured responses for the user researcher to sift through a=
nd manually tag and categorize, followed by a presentation to the exec or p=
roduct team, from which a decision may or may not be made, three months aft=
er the question was asked.
That process makes sense for big, irreversible projects like rebrands, mark=
et expansions, and=C2=A0 product extensions, but it=E2=80=99s far too slow =
for most of the things for which a tech company needs user insights. So com=
panies often just skip structured customer research, and rely on numbers an=
d anecdotes to make product decisions. That=E2=80=99s a problem: companies =
have modern tools like Amplitude and Segment to tell them what is happening=
 in their product, but only slow, outdated, and complex tools to tell them =
why.
That=E2=80=99s why Glasgow started UserLeap [https://email.mg2.substack.com=
/c/eJxNUcuKxCAQ_JrkNsFHTPTgYWHZ3xCjPRmZqMHHLvn7NZmBXRCF6q6ustroAmtMh9xjLv15=
qXLsIAP85A1KgdTXDEk5K_FEOGWj6K0cLeaM9y6rewLw2m2ypAr9XpfNGV1cDBcDIcL6hxSLQXY=
aBZkALL8TcZ8tmgXiABxRzl66uloHwYCEb0hHDNBv8lHKnjv60ZGvdk4nG-h9MNGfCG3gVItXOd=
ZkoKOfu3ZW7do8D0UQwTdEbxi_mzxYV31rugy_QaN946zh4jZa_vdxJ88ZiGKMKZvwPOBBzMYSq=
6eFYcYx0EVzsdhZEEz51KBuRH4lQ65LLm3cabRPMsSyxOTC2srPh_awXYWWlmqvr8GVQ0HQywb2=
FWR57eNyqlYIkNqerNKlbQGzcUaCM4LfwbWkKWV4HhvQlG1srPAn-gsrpKFn].
Meet UserLeap
After ExtraBux, Glasgow went on to be the founding PM at four more companie=
s, including Vurb (acquired by Snap) and Weebly (acquired by Square). Over =
the course of those experiences, he learned three lessons [https://email.mg=
2.substack.com/c/eJxFkEuOwyAQRE8Tdrb4GIMXLGYz17D4dGwUDBbgGeX200kWIyEaulVU8b=
ztsJX6NGdpnby2tT9PMBl-W4LeoZKrQV1jMGzmWshpIcFMgWmpSWzrvQIcNibT6wXkvFyK3vZY8=
ltBKZdkN9pxR6mm99nJu1w489ID90ooZd288I-vvUKE7MHAD9RnyUCS2Xs_20183fg3rleSBPYc=
fTnw-lJhEUOC1kpuQ8STrRnCYNtgh3u5coh5G85j3PuRSDScckYFY0zImamRjYvygQeLwZjUDIS=
zenFBYUahZ2zdJnpsfGyXa936x8uZVJNLd6Xi0zh-7PaA9B7g91esx5Vjf66QrUsQPmT6B_Cb1b=
pBhorgw2o7YmVyUnTRkjP5IYHohJBMTdhA51BQlf9N_wAb05Hy]:=C2=A0
Customers have crucial insights, but it=E2=80=99s impossible to read their =
minds.
Analyzing a lot of open-ended, qualitative data is hard and tedious.
Customer research tools haven=E2=80=99t kept up with the modern Product Man=
ager tech stack.
Glasgow left Weebly in 2018 to build UserLeap based on those insights. User=
Leap flips the traditional user research process on its head, enabling cont=
inuous user research, through ongoing microsurveys embedded in the product.=
=C2=A0
UserLeap is like Stripe for Research. It=E2=80=99s trivial to plug in, and =
that ease masks a ton of complexity and power behind the scenes. Here=E2=80=
=99s how it works:=C2=A0
Sign up for a free UserLeap account [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxNU=
cuKxCAQ_JrkNsFHTPTgYWHZ3xCjPRmZqMHHLvn7NZmBXRCF6q6ustroAmtMh9xjLv15qXLsIAP8=
5A1KgdTXDEk5K_FEOGWj6K0cLeaM9y6rewLw2m2ypAr9XpfNGV1cDBcDIcL6hxSLQXYaBZkALL8=
TcZ8tmgXiABxRzl66uloHwYCEb0hHDNBv8lHKnjv60ZGvdk4nG-h9MNGfCG3gVItXOdZkoKOfu3=
ZW7do8D0UQwTdEbxi_mzxYV31rugy_QaN946zh4jZa_vdxJ88ZiGKMKZvwPOBBzMYSq6eFYcYx0=
EVzsdhZEEz51KBuRH4lQ65LLm3cabRPMsSyxOTC2srPh_awXYWWlmqvr8GVQ0HQywb2FWR57eNy=
qlYIkNqerNKlbQGzcUaCM4LfwbWkKWV4HhvQlG1srPAn-gsrpKFn].=C2=A0
Drop in a couple lines of code.
Anyone on the team can spin up microsurveys, using a library of templates [=
https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxNUUmK5DAQfI19a6PVy0GHgWG-IbRkuURbktEyjX=
_fWa6GGRASuURkKNKZBnsulzpzbePr0u06QSX4qge0BmXsFYoOXtGZrVyKbfRKeLrKdQxVPwpAN=
OFQrXQYz26P4EwLOd0IQpgcn0rYB12MsNISKzlykE14sixufRhhDH_PNd0HSA4U_IVy5QTjoZ6t=
nXXgvwb2B89LyQHmnFyOGDaI54H66_Rs8Rg4tsy9RV1zLw4G_vs0wevTuM9LM8LoB-EflP40RfC=
hR2y65f8knYmI2dONRVj9z4agXhyEU0q5nOky0WlbnGfezFZSuVLg1qyb9cvGKF9nTA2CxJ1Ntd=
vakO4leywq5WZzCWnH8ufTRDjuAnqn8Y09hXZpSMYe4N-2tvd2bqV6hwQFf-21abgTKsVCtlUyK=
t82ou9oMV0EJnCyz4hK_4Z-A2M5pxw] or their own imagination.
UserLeap is built on an events-based architecture, meaning that surveys are=
 triggered based on things that a user does on the site.=C2=A0
Users answer short quantitative or qualitative questions.=C2=A0
UserLeap's AI groups similar answers and presents categorized insights, sav=
ing hours of manual tagging and sorting in spreadsheets. A human review pro=
cess ensures high accuracy, while also providing data which allows the AI t=
o become increasingly more accurate.
By making the process fast and easy, UserLeap is trying to answer the quest=
ion: how can any customer facing employee become a user researcher?=C2=A0
In one of my favorite pieces written in the last year, Why Figma Wins [http=
s://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkEGOwyAMRU9TdhNhCAksWMxmrhERcBPUBCogU-X24z=
aLkdC3_I315eddwyWX0z5zbewtUzufaBO-6oatYWFHxTLFYGEQWqresGD7AFppFut0L4i7i5tt5=
UD2POYtetdiTp8NzoViqzV3rU1AzX2QWg3S3YVSOIYeTBAehivXHSFi8mjxF8uZE7LNrq09601-=
38QPvccrP_zqYup83qkXXHAqfCABQ_Jaz697XHb39YqpksGipU_AJQBINcDYQWdGH0Rww6xAaUA=
5O23mMBoBUg9k3Xq-L6Krx1yb8493Fis25TbnEtNC48fqdtw-A7p4orofKbZzwuTmDcMFo11MP3=
imBRMWYh0m14gkqH7kRisB6jqeaEmpYOzJoOSQaSv9h_4BFQ2KfQ], Kevin Kwok wrote:
The core insight of Figma is that design is larger than just designers.=C2=
=A0
UserLeap=E2=80=99s parallel insight is that user research is larger than ju=
st user researchers. In other words, UserLeap is attempting to do for custo=
mer research what Looker is doing for business intelligence and Figma is do=
ing for design. By pushing user research tools throughout the organization,=
 companies can glean valuable insights dramatically more quickly.=C2=A0
Source: Kevin Kwok (adapted by Packy)
So how do you build a product that turns anyone into a user researcher? You=
 make the assumption that those people don=E2=80=99t know how to do user re=
search, and that they=E2=80=99re busy. You make it easy, you make it intuit=
ive, and you make it fast.=C2=A0
